t               = -8\n|timezone_DST             = PDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -7\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_ft             = \n|coordinates              = {{coord|45|26|9|N|122|39|14|W|type:city_region:US-OR_source:gnis-1136234|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 97219\n|area_code                = [[Area codes 503 and 971|503 and 971]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = \n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1136234<ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis|id=1136234|name=Dunthorpe, Oregon}}</ref>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Dunthorpe''' is an affluent<ref name=\"OregonLive.com\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/education/index.ssf/2017/09/riverdale_officials_tips_for_s.html|title=Riverdale educators offer tips for schools wanting to boost student achievement|work=OregonLive.com|access-date=2017-09-20|language=en-US}}</ref> [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated]] [[suburb]] of [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], United States. It is located just south of the Portland city limits and north of the [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] line on the west side of the [[Willamette River]]. [[Lewis & Clark College]], [[Tryon Creek State Park]], and [[Lake Oswego, Oregon|Lake Oswego]] are nearby.\n\n==History==\nIn January 1916, [[William M. Ladd]]'s Ladd Estate Company purchased {{convert|215|acre|km2}} from the soon to be dissolved [[Oregon Iron & Steel Company]] for $1.<ref name=\"maccoll\">{{cite book\n | last = MacColl\n | first = E. Kimbark\n | title = The Growth of a City: Power and Politics in Portland, Oregon 1915-1950\n | year = 1979\n | publisher = The Georgian Press\n | location = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]]\n | isbn = 0-9603408-1-5\n}}</ref>  The company drafted very specific provisions for the Dunthorpe development, including: Only residential buildings were allowed, except for outbuildings to house domestic animals; Swine and goats were prohibited; The minimum cost of a house was $3000; and the sale of \"intoxicating liquor\" was prohibited.<ref name=\"maccoll\"/>\n\n==Arts and culture==\n\n===Museums and other points of interest===\nOne of the notable attractions of the area is the [[Elk Rock Gardens of the Bishop's Close]], an estate which consists of {{convert|13|acre|m2}} on a high bluff and is located on the western bank of the Willamette River. The property includes approximately {{convert|6|acre|ha}} of cultivated [[English garden|English-style gardens]] that were designed by the New York firm of [[Frederick Law Olmsted|Olmsted and Son]], who also designed [[Central Park]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"maccoll\"/> The garden is open to the public seven days a week and is widely known for the many varieties of [[magnolia]]s as well as for examples of many other native and exotic plants.<ref>[http://www.diocese-oregon.org/theclose/ The Bishop's Close] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090609063300/http://www.diocese-oregon.org/theclose/ |date=2009-06-09 }} - Episcopal Church, Oregon Diocese</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n<!-- Note:\n\u00b7 Only people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here. This establishes notability.\n\u00b7 The biographical article must mention how they are associated with Dunthorpe, whether born, raised, or residing.\n\u00b7 The fact of their association should have a reliable source cited\n\u00b7 Alphabetical by last name please\n\u00b7 All others will be deleted without further explanation\n-->\n*[[LaMarcus Aldridge]] (1985\u2013), professional basketball player\n*[[Brandin Cooks]] (1993\u2013), professional football player\n*[[Maurice E. Crumpacker]] (1886\u20131927), U.S. congressman from Oregon \n*[[Clyde Drexler]] (1962\u2013), retired professional basketball player and Hall of Famer\n*[[Channing Frye]] (1983\u2013), professional basketball player\n*[[Danny Glover]] (1946\u2013), actor\n*[[Bob Packwood]] (1932\u2013), former U.S. senator from Oregon \n*[[Terry Porter]] (1963\u2013), professional basketball coach and former player\n*[[Linus Torvalds]] (1969\u2013), software engineer; developer of Linux\n*[[William McCormick (diplomat)|William McCormick]] (1939-), US Ambassador to New Zealand\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{GNIS|1136234|name=Dunthorpe}}\n\n{{Multnomah County, Oregon}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Portland metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Multnomah County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Willamette River]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Dunthorpe\n|official_name            = \n|settlement_type          = [[Unincorporated area|Unincorporated suburb]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = The Bishops Close Dunthorpe Oregon.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = Entrance to [[Elk Rock Gardens of the Bishop's Close]] in Dunthorpe\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map              = USA Oregon#USA\n|pushpin_label_position   = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location within the state of Oregon\n|pushpin_mapsize          = \n|image_map                = \n|map_caption              = Location within Multnomah county\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Oregon]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Oregon|County]]\n|subdivision_