Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], United States. It is located just south of the Portland city limits and north of the [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] line on the west side of the [[Willamette River]]. [[Lewis & Clark College]], [[Tryon Creek State Park]], and [[Lake Oswego, Oregon|Lake Oswego]] are nearby.\n\n==History==\nIn January 1916, [[William M. Ladd]]'s Ladd Estate Company purchased {{convert|215|acre|km2}} from the soon to be dissolved [[Oregon Iron & Steel Company]] for $1.<ref name=\"maccoll\">{{cite book\n | last = MacColl\n | first = E. Kimbark\n | title = The Growth of a City: Power and Politics in Portland, Oregon 1915-1950\n | year = 1979\n | publisher = The Georgian Press\n | location = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]]\n | isbn = 0-9603408-1-5\n}}</ref>  The company drafted very specific provisions for the Dunthorpe development, including: Only residential buildings were allowed, except for outbuildings to house domestic animals; Swine and goats were prohibited; The minimum cost of a house was $3000; and the sale of \"intoxicating liquor\" was prohibited.<ref name=\"maccoll\"/>\n\n==Arts and culture==\n\n===Museums and other points of interest===\nOne of the notable attractions of the area is the [[Elk Rock Gardens of the Bishop's Close]], an estate which consists of {{convert|13|acre|m2}} on a high bluff on the western bank of the Willamette River. The property includes approximately {{convert|6|acre|ha}} of cultivated [[English garden|English-style gardens]] that were designed by the New York firm of [[Frederick Law Olmsted|Olmsted and Son]], who also designed [[Central Park]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"maccoll\"/> The garden is open to the public seven days a week and is widely known for the many varieties of [[magnolia]]s as well as for examples of many other native and exotic plants.<ref>[http://www.diocese-oregon.org/theclose/ The Bishop's Close] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090609063300/http://www.diocese-oregon.org/theclose/ |date=2009-06-09 }} - Episcopal Church, Oregon Diocese</ref>\n\n==Education==\nRiverdale School District in Dunthorpe is among the best academically performing school districts in Oregon by various measures, including standardized test scores, which are frequently the best in the state.<ref name=\"OregonLive.com\"/> According to [[24/7 Wall St.'s]] analysis of U.S. Census data from 2006 through 2010, the Riverdale School District is the third richest school district in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://247wallst.com/2012/06/06/americas-richest-school-districts/|title=America\u2019s Richest School Districts - 24/7 Wall St.|date=6 June 2012|work=247wallst.com|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/economy/2012/06/08/americas-richest-school-districts/|title=America\u2019s Richest School Districts|work=Fox Business|accessdate=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004073841/http://www.foxbusiness.com/economy/2012/06/08/americas-richest-school-districts/|archive-date=4 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/08/richest-school-districts-_n_1581650.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Alex | last=Kuczynskibrown | title=The Richest School Districts In America | date=2012-06-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.oregonlive.com/education/index.ssf/2012/06/riverdale_school_district_amon.html | work=The Oregonian | title=Riverdale School District ranks as one of the nation's richest public school systems | date=2012-06-11}}</ref>\n\nAs a community, Dunthorpe was historically anchored by Riverdale Grade School. In the early 1990s, the [[Oregon Legislative Assembly|Oregon legislature]] decreed that all school districts should have both primary and secondary schools, and expected smaller school districts like Riverdale to merge.  While an old grade school was purchased and renovated for use as [[Riverdale High School (Portland, Oregon)|Riverdale High School]], high school students were bussed to nearby [[Marylhurst University]] in the neighboring city of [[West Linn, Oregon|West Linn]], where space was leased by the school district.\n\nIn September 2002, the high school moved into its permanent building, a renovation and expansion of an existing but unused public school structure. In November 2008, the voters of Riverdale School District passed a measure authorizing the District to issue bonds in an amount up to $21.5 million to renovate and expand the existing grade school building.<ref>[http://www.riverdale.k12.or.us/riverdale/site/default.asp]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208214222/http://www.riverdale.k12.or.us/riverdale/site/default.asp |date=February 8, 2009 }}</ref> In July 2009, the original grade school was demolished.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2009/07/riverdale_grade_school_comes_d.html|title=Riverdale Grade School comes down after controversy|date=2009-07-07|work=[[The Oregonian]]|accessdate=2009-07-12}}</ref> The building was rebuilt in the style of the original in 2010.\n\n==Notable residents==\n<!-- Note:\n\u00b7 Only people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here. This establishes notability.\n\u00b7 The biographical article must mention how they are associated with Dunthorpe, whether born, raised, or residing.\n\u00b7 The fact of their association should have a reliable source cited\n\u00b7 Alphabetical by last name please\n\u00b7 All others will be deleted without further explanation\n-->\n*[[LaMarcus Aldridge]] (1985\u2013), professional basketball player\n*[[Brandin Cooks]] (1993\u2013), professional football player\n*[[Maurice E. Crumpacker]] (1886\u20131927), U.S. congressman from Oregon \n*[[Clyde Drexler]] (1962\u2013), retired professional basketball player and Hall of Famer\n*[[Channing Frye]] (1983\u2013), professional basketball player\n*[[Danny Glover]] (1946\u2013), actor\n*[[Bob Packwood]] (1932\u2013), former U.S. senator from Oregon \n*[[Terry Porter]] (1963\u2013), professional basketball coach and former player\n*[[Linus Torvalds]] (1969\u2013), software engineer; developer of Linux\n*[[William McCormick (diplomat)|William McCormick]] (1939-), US Ambassador to New Zealand\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{GNIS|1136234|name=Dunthorpe}}\n\n{{Multnomah County, Oregon}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Portland metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Multnomah County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Willamette River]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:8071:aab:b300:8d76:a2cf:5486:db62", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added wording)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dunthorpe,_Oregon"}
{"title_page": "Syro-Lebanese in Egypt", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=December 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Syro-Lebanese in Egypt \n|image = Youssef Chahine, prominent Egyptian filmmaker and director of Syro-Lebanese ancestry.jpg\n|poptime = \n|regions = \n|languages = [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[French language|French]]\n|religions = \n* Majority: [[Christianity]] ([[Greek Orthodox]], [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Melkite Greek Catholic]], [[Maronite Catholic]])\n* Minority: [[Islam]] ([[Shia Islam|Shia]]/[[Sunni Islam|Sunni]]), [[Judaism]]\n|related = [[Greeks in Egypt]], [[Armenians in Egypt]], [[Italians in Egypt]], [[Maltese in Egypt]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Syro-Lebanese of Egypt''' ({{lang-arz|'''\u0634\u0648\u0627\u0645 \u0645\u0635\u0631'''}}, [[Romanization of Arabic|transliterated]]: ''Shawam Masr'') ({{lang-fr|Syro-Libanais d'Egypte}}), also known as the '''Levantines of Egypt''', are an ethnic minority group in [[Egypt]]. They are Egyptians who have ancestry originating from the [[Levant]], mostly what is now [[Syria]] and [[Lebanon]]. The majority of Egypt's historic Syro-Lebanese community is [[Christians|Christian]] ([[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Melkite Greek Catholic]], [[Greek Orthodox]], and [[Maronite Catholic]]), although some families were also [[Muslim]] ([[Shia Islam|Shia]]/[[Sunni Islam|Sunni]]) and [[Jewish]].\n\nSince antiquity, there has always been a Levantine presence in Egypt, however, they started becoming a distinctive minority in Egypt around the early 18th century. The majority of Syro-Lebanese migrants who arrived in Egypt during this time were [[Francophone|French-speaking]] and highly influenced by the [[European Culture]]. By the dawn of the 20th century, the Syro-Lebanese of Egypt were considered a powerful and cosmopolitan community that played an important role in both Egypt's economy and culture. \n\nDue to the rise in nationalism along with the loss of economic freedoms during the 1950s, a part of Egypt's Syro-Lebanese community left the country immigrating to the [[Americas]], [[Europe]], and [[Australia]], as well as many returning to their native Lebanon (especially [[Beirut]]) and Syria. Notable descendants of Egypt's Syro-Lebanese community include the world-renowned Egyptian actor [[Omar Sharif]] (born Michel Chalhoub) and Egyptian film director [[Youssef Chahine]].\n\n==History==\nThe relations between Egypt and the [[Levant]] go back to ancient times. However, the earliest instance of modern Levantine migration to Egypt happened after 1724, when a schism in the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch]] resulted in a separate branch of Levantine Christians attached to Rome known as the [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Melkite Greek Catholics]]. Once the Syrian and Lebanese Greek Orthodox community was split, a migratory flow resulted in which Melkite Greek Catholics began leaving cities such as [[Damascus]], [[Aleppo]], [[Zahle]], and [[Sidon]] to move to Egypt. Regarding an early [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite]] presence in Egypt dating from the 18th century, it is said that the [[Holy See|Holy see of Rome]] appointed two Maronite priests to serve as advisers to the [[Franciscans]] who came from the Custody of the Holy Land to [[Evangelism|evangelize]] Egypt because \"no one knows the land and mentality of the Coptic Christians like the Maronites\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Catholics In Egypt Reflect Church's Rich And Varied Traditions |newspaper=L'Osservatore Romano|date=1 March 2000|volume=Weekly Edition in English|pages=6, 7|url=http://www.ewtn.com/library/CHISTORY/EGPTCATH.HTM}}</ref>[[File:Ikonenwand der Kirche des St. Saba(s), Alexandria, \u00c4gypten.jpg|thumb|Iconostasis of the Greek Orthodox Church of St. Sabbas, Alexandria, Egypt|235x235px]]Later during the mid-1800s, due to the [[1860 Lebanon conflict|political conflict]] that existed in Lebanon and Syria between the [[Christians|Christian]] and [[Druze]] religious sects, many [[Syrian people|Syrian]] and [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] Christians, as well as [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] and [[Jordanian people|Jordanian]] Christians to some extent, migrated to Egypt under the rule of [[Muhammad Ali Pasha]]. These Syro-Lebanese or [[Levant]]ine Christians, known in Egyptian Arabic as the \"Shawam\", were either of Greek Orthodox or Catholic (Melkite or Maronite) extraction. The reason immigrants from Lebanon and Syria were considered one ethnic group was because during the mid-1800s, Lebanon was not yet an independent state and was still part of [[Ottoman Syria]], or \"Bilad al-Sham\" in Arabic, hence their label as \"Shawam\" or \"Shami\".  Muhammad Ali Pasha endorsed various ethnic and religious groups, including Syro-Lebanese, [[Greeks in Egypt|Greeks]], [[Armenians in Egypt|Armenians]], [[Jews in Egypt|Jews]], [[Italians in Egypt|Italians]], and [[Maltese in Egypt|Maltese]] to settle in Egypt.<ref>{{cite book|last=Sol\u00e9|first=Robert|title=Birds of Passage|year=2000|publisher=Harvill Press|location=London, England|isbn=1860466974|url=https://archive.org/details/birdsofpassage00robe}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Sol\u00e9|first=Robert|title=Le Tarbouche|year=1992|publisher=Seuil|location=Paris|isbn=978-2020205108}}</ref>\nFrom the building of the Suez Canal to the creation of modern Downtown Cairo, Egypt\u2019s rulers went on a spending spree that attracted migrants from across the world. The Syro-Lebanese, who first migrated were [[French language|French-speaking]] and well-educated (largely due to [[Europe|European]] and [[American Home Missionary Society|American missionaries]]), had a mindset in the British-run economy of Egypt at the time. As a result, they were able to flourish as an energetic and cosmopolitan community until the [[Gamal Abdel Nasser|Nasser]] era of the mid-1950s, that adopted an Arabization mind set for the entire region.  Most of the Syro-Lebanese were self-employed businessmen or [[Artisan|craftsmen]] and had more of a \"[[Westernization|Westernized]]\" education than others. [[Robert Sol\u00e9]], a [[France|French]] author of Levantine-Egyptian descent, describes all of these aspects of the Syro-Lebanese community in Egypt in his book, \"Birds of Passage\", as well as in his other publications.<ref>{{cite book|last=Sol\u00e9|first=Robert|title=Birds of Passage|year=2000|publisher=Harvill Press|location=London, England|isbn=1860466974|url=https://archive.org/details/birdsofpassage00robe}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Sol\u00e9|first=Robert|title=Le Tarbouche|year=1992|publisher=Seuil|location=Paris|isbn=978-2020205108}}</ref>\n\nThe Syro-Lebanese established [[Greek Catholic Church|Melkite Greek-Catholic]] and Maronite Catholic churches throughout many areas of Egypt such as [[Cairo]], [[Alexandria]], [[Mansoura]], [[Suez]], [[Port Said]], and [[Tanta]]. The Greek Orthodox Syro-Lebanese experienced conflict trying to establish their own churches under their native [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch|Antiochian]] denomination, and became under the jurisdiction of the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Alexandria]], which was mainly run by an ethnic Greek clergy. \nIn Egypt, many families of Syro-Lebanese origin became successful in Egypt's business sector along with the established Armenian and Greek communities. Many were involved in Egypt's booming cotton industry. The famous Egyptian newspaper, \"[[Al-Ahram]]\", was created by the Syro-Lebanese Takla family in Egypt.<ref>{{cite book|last=Khoury|first=G\u00e9rard D.|title=S\u00e9lim Takla 1895-1945: Une Contribution \u00e0 L'ind\u00e9pendance Du Liban|year=2004|publisher=Karthala Editions|isbn=284586549X|pages=556|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iluH1VqaI5UC&pg=RA2-PA21-IA4&lpg=RA2-PA21-IA4&dq=takla+al-ahram&source=bl&ots=0Ndyxbiba-&sig=HvZt7lNGQuqPDa_VChc7ZGpB8bM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6zHRULeAF-XL0AGH4oDAAw&ved=0CEgQ6AEwAw}}</ref>\nSyro-Lebanese families dominated the publishing industry, owning major printing houses like Dar al-Hilal (est. 1892), which gave them enormous influence on the country\u2019s cultural life. Even Rose al-Youssef, the quintessential Egyptian cultural figure from the first half of the twentieth century, was originally Levantine of Turkish descent. The (then) irreverent political and literary magazine she founded and named after herself continues to this day, albeit in state hands like Al-Ahram. Even the material culture of Cairo has been suffused by Syro-Lebanese influence. The most prolific architect in Central Cairo between the 1930s and 1960s was Antoine Selim Nahhas, who is seen as the one of the modernist architects in Egypt. Nahhas, who built among other important buildings the Beirut National Museum, established a wildly successful practice in Cairo, where he designed buildings for the rich and famous, often Levantine-Egyptians like himself, such as the actor Farid al-Atrash. [[File:Syro-Lebanese Christian women.jpg|thumb|235x235px|Christian Syro-Lebanese women in [[Cairo]], Egypt (1950)|alt=]]Even though the number of Levantine-Egyptians still in Egypt is drastically low today, the Syro-Lebanese community retains its strength in some aspects of the cultural and entertainment industries. Cairo\u2019s most famous restaurant entrepreneur, Nisha Sursock, comes from a prominent Beirut Greek Orthodox family.<ref>{{cite news|last=El Amrani|first=Issandr|title=Lebanese Played a Crucial Role in Shaping Modern Egyptian Culture|newspaper=The Daily Star|date=2004-02-27}}</ref>\n\nThe Levantine community in Egypt counted more than 100,000 members at the turn of the 20th century: civil servants, hairdressers, cobblers, drivers, engineers, dentists, doctors, shopkeepers, painters. Their aggregate wealth was reckoned at one and a half billion francs, that is 10% of the Egyptian GDP. Those who had capital invested it in small businesses (oil, soaps, tobacco, patisserie). Others created more important companies trading or producing salt, sodium, textiles, perfume, wood, silk. This economic success led to the foundation of schools, clubs, and charities, generally linked to a place of worship which was most of the time a church. A minority returned to their home village but the majority remained \u201csemi-detached\u201d, settling for several generations in Egypt without for all that involving themselves fully in the host society.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fadel|first=Marwan Abi|title=Syro-Lebanese Migration Towards Egypt|url=http://hemed.univ-lemans.fr/cours2010/en/co/module_5.html}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Mansoura]], a city that used to be under huge [[France|French]] and [[Europe|European]] influence. The Levantines excelled equally as lawyers, cotton trade entrepreneurs, large real-estate owners, medical doctors and pharmacists, department store and restaurant and hotel owners, bankers, and financial agents. They were also renowned for their large estates, like the heirs of Comte Khalil de Saab and the Sussah family, Naguib Bek Sursuq, and the 'izba of George Daoud. They owned several international hotels. For instance, Khalil Bahari owned the Semiramis Hotel, which included the best restaurant in Mansoura. Dhaher al-Rayyes was the owner of the largest hotel in Mansoura, the [[Paris]] Hotel, while his brother, Bichara, owned the Claridge Hotel, and a third brother owned the Imperial Hotel. The Shawam of Mansoura occupied key positions as medical doctors, showing why nearly half of the doctors in Mansoura used to be foreigners at that time, mainly Europeans. Levantines also notably became bank managers. Some Shawam earned the titles of Count, like Count Saab and Count Chedid. Others earned the titles of Pasha and Bek, while a few even earned the title of Emir (Prince), like the Lutfallah, and subsequently the [[Sursock family|Sursock]], family.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Abaza|first1=Mona|title=The Cotton Plantation Remembered: An Egyptian Family Story|date=15 November 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press}}</ref>\n\n==Identity==\n\nThe term \"Syro-Lebanese\" or \"Syrian-Lebanese\" is an [[umbrella term]] to identify the people of the Levant, especially the generations who lived when most of the region was known as [[Bilad al-Sham]], or [[Greater Syria]]. Between the late 18th century and early 20th century, thousands of Levantines left their homeland, mainly due to warfare, and Egypt became the first stop for many who aimed to reach the Western world. In Egypt, as well as other nations with Syrian and Lebanese diaspora communities, the Levantines mainly identified by religion and city of origin, rather than by ethnicity. For example, one could identify as a \"[[Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholic]] from [[Zahle]]\", while another could identify as \"[[Greek Orthodox Church|Greek Orthodox]] from [[Aleppo]]\". For the most part, religious denomination and city of origin were more important to the Levantines than an actual \"Levantine\" or \"Syro-Lebanese\" identity. This may explain why it was generally easy for the Syro-Lebanese to assimilate into their newly found homelands and mix with other Christian populations, especially in Egypt. However, the Egyptians, and especially the Coptic [[Coptic Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christians]], could easily point out a Levantine's non-native background due to their foreign Christian background, if not by their overall lighter skin tone. After generations of living in Egypt, most of this community's descendants, now with Egyptian nationality, tended to identify more as \"Egyptian\", rather than \"Levantine\", \"Syrian\", or \"Lebanese\", while still maintaining their original [[christian Denomination|Christian sect]] of identity. However, intermarriage for the Levantines in Egypt eventually became more common after generations, either with native Coptic Christians whom are in millions or with other foreign minority Christians such as [[Greek people|Greeks]], [[Armenian people|Armenians]], and [[Maltese people|Maltese]]. There was much less intermarriage between Levantine Christians and native Muslims, as marriage between Christians and Muslims is still considered taboo in Egypt.\n\n==Churches==\n\n[[Christianity]] is the dominant religion among Egyptians of Syro-Lebanese descent. The majority follow Greek Orthodox (originally [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch|Greek Orthodox Antiochian]], but then falling under [[Greek Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Greek Orthodox Alexandrian]] jurisdiction in Egypt), a founder sect of Christianity since the [[Greco-Roman world|Greco-Roman Egypt]], [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church]] and the [[Maronite Church]]. With [[Catholic school|Catholic education]] being popular among [[Christianity|Christian]] families in Egypt, many Levantines also naturally attended [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic churches]].\n\n\u2022 Greek Orthodox Churches ([[Greece|Greek]] [[Christian denomination|Church]]es):\n\n* [[Cairo]] - Greek Orthodox Church of St. George, Greek Catholic Cathedral of the Resurrection, Greek Catholic Annunciation Church, Greek Catholic Immaculate Conception Church, Greek Catholic St. George Church, Greek Catholic St. Mary of Peace Church, Greek Catholic St. Joseph Church, Greek Catholic St. Cyril Church\n* [[Alexandria, Egypt|Alexandria]] - Greek Catholic Dormition Cathedral, Saint Sabbas Greek Orthodox Church, Greek Catholic Immaculate Conception, Greek Catholic St. Joseph, \n* [[Damanhur]] - Saints Constantine and Helena Greek Orthodox Church\n* [[Damietta]] - Saint Nicholas Greek Orthodox Church, and an old Greek Catholic Church that was converted to a Coptic Orthodox Church.\n* [[El-Mahalla El-Kubra]] - Saint George Greek Orthodox Church, Saint Augustine Catholic Church\n* [[Mansoura]] - Saint Nicholas Greek Orthodox Church, Saints Athanasius and Cyril Greek Orthodox Church, Dormition Greek Catholic Church\n* [[Port Said]] - Saint Elias Greek Catholic Church\n* [[Shibin Al Kawm, Al Minufiyah|Shibin Al Kawm]] - Saint Spyridon Greek Orthodox Church\n* [[Tanta]] - Saint George Greek Orthodox Church, Dormition of the Holy Virgin Greek Orthodox Church, Presentation of the Lord Greek Orthodox Church, Saint Anne Greek Catholic Church\n* [[Zagazig]] - Three Hierarchs Greek Orthodox Church, Dormition of the Holy Virgin Greek Orthodox Church, Saint Joseph Catholic Church\n\n==Diaspora==\nThe number of Syro-Lebanese in Egypt has decreased due to the nationalization policies of the [[Gamal Abdel Nasser|Nasser]] government after the [[1952 Revolution|1952 revolution]].{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} As a result, there has been extensive migrations to other countries such as [[Canada]], the [[United States]], [[France]], [[Australia]], [[Switzerland]], and [[Belgium]]. The remaining Syro-Lebanese in Egypt began integrating into the rest of Egyptian society, including extensive intermarriage with [[Coptic Orthodox Church|Coptic Christians]] and Muslims. Today, most Egyptians of Levantine roots tend to identify more as Egyptian rather than Syrian or Lebanese, even though some traditionally belong to [[List of Christian denominations|Christian denominations]] like [[Greek Orthodox Church|Greek Orthodox]] other than Egypt's native [[Coptic Orthodox]], [[Coptic Catholic]], or native Protestant churches.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tewfik|first1=Paul Shoukri|title=The Syro-Lebanese of Egypt|date=17 December 2012}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nA large number of Syro-Lebanese families from Egypt now reside in [[Montreal]]; The communities of [[St. George Antiochian Orthodox Church (Montreal)|St. George Antiochian Orthodox Church]], Saint-Sauveur Melkite Greek-Catholic Cathedral, and St. Maron Church (Maronite Catholic), have many parishioners who are from Egypt or are descendants of Egyptian immigrants. Records from 1987 show that up to 250 families out of the total 1,300 registered families of [[St. George Antiochian Orthodox Church (Montreal)|St. George's Antiochian Orthodox Church of Montreal]] were originally from Egypt. In that same year, the Melkite [[Saint Sauveur Cathedral]] of Montreal reported to have approximately two-thirds of its 3,000 registered families originating from Egypt. Records from the St. Maron Church in Montreal show that out of its total 1,284 registered families in 1987, 600 of them were [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronites]] from Egypt.<ref>{{cite book |last=Magocsi |first=Paul Robert |year=1999 |title=Encyclopedia of Canada's Peoples |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dbUuX0mnvQMC&pg=PA460 |publisher=University of Toronto Press |page=460 |isbn=978-0-8020-2938-6}}</ref>\n\nExample of those [[Greek Catholic]] melkite [[Christianity|Christians]] who faced oppression from Nasser regime and was forced to get out residing in [[Europe]], [[Americas]] and [[Australia]] are; Absi, Ackaoui, Allouche, Anhoury, Arcache, Assouad, Ayrout, Ayoub, Azzam, Barakat, Behna, Bichara, Bittar, Boulad, Bahri, Cassis, Chahine, Chalhoub, Dabbour, Debban\u00e9, Doummar, Dahan, Eid, Fakhoury, Gargoura, Gorra, Haddad, Hawawini, Hobeika, Jaouich, Kassab, Kahil, Kahla, Kheir, Kfouri, Klat, Karam, Lahham, M\u00e9dawar, Michaka, Mirza, Mitri, Naoum, Nahas, Nimr, Rabbath, Rathie, Sarkis, Sednaoui, Sabet, Sabbagh, Samman, Sayeh, Sakakini, Sabounghi, Sol\u00e9, Toutounji,Talka, Tawil, Tagher, Tawa, Yansouni, Zalka, Zayat, Zananiri, Zogheb. <ref>{{cite web|last=Manzoni|first=Sandro|title=Alexandrie Info|url=http://www.aaha.ch/bulletins/pdf/Bull-26.pdf|accessdate=26 March 2020|quote=La plus grande partie de cette communaut\u00e9 a quite l'Egypte apres lets \u00e9v\u00e9nements de 1956 et les vagues de nationalisations nass\u00e9riennes. Beaucoup se sont install\u00e9s au Liban, en Europe (France et Suisse) et Am\u00e9rique (surtout Canada). }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Naaman|first=Abdallah|title=Histoire des Orientaux de France du Ier au XXe si\u00e8cle|year=2004|publisher=Ellipses|location=Paris|isbn=978-2729814052}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Habib Tawa]], French historian, specialist of this issue\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Demographics of Egypt}}\n{{Lebanese diaspora}}\n{{Syrian diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Asian diaspora in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Eastern Catholicism in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodoxy in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Egyptian people of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:Egyptian people of Palestinian descent]]\n[[Category:Egyptian people of Syrian descent]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Greek Orthodoxy in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Egypt]] \n[[Category:Jordanian diaspora]]\n[[Category:Lebanese diaspora by country|Egypt]]\n[[Category:Lebanese diaspora in Africa]]\n[[Category:Maronites by country]]\n[[Category:Melkite Greek Catholic Church in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Palestinian diaspora in the Arab world]]\n[[Category:Syrian diaspora in the Arab world]]\n[[Category:Syrian diaspora in Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=December 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Syro-Lebanese in Egypt \n|image = Youssef Chahine, prominent Egyptian filmmaker and director of Syro-Lebanese ancestry.jpg\n|poptime = \n|regions = \n|languages = [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[French language|French]]\n|religions = \n* Majority: [[Christianity]] ([[Greek Orthodox]], [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Melkite Greek Catholic]], [[Maronite Catholic]])\n* Minority: [[Islam]] ([[Shia Islam|Shia]]/[[Sunni Islam|Sunni]]), [[Judaism]]\n|related = [[Greeks in Egypt]], [[Armenians in Egypt]], [[Italians in Egypt]], [[Maltese in Egypt]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Syro-Lebanese of Egypt''' ({{lang-arz|'''\u0634\u0648\u0627\u0645 \u0645\u0635\u0631'''}}, [[Romanization of Arabic|transliterated]]: ''Shawam Masr'') ({{lang-fr|Syro-Libanais d'Egypte}}), also known as the '''Levantines of Egypt''', are an ethnic minority group in [[Egypt]]. They are Egyptians who have ancestry originating from the [[Levant]], mostly what is now [[Syria]] and [[Lebanon]]. The majority of Egypt's historic Syro-Lebanese community is [[Christians|Christian]] ([[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Melkite Greek Catholic]], [[Greek Orthodox]], and [[Maronite Catholic]]), although some families were also [[Muslim]] ([[Shia Islam|Shia]]/[[Sunni Islam|Sunni]]) and [[Jewish]].\n\nSince antiquity, there has always been a Levantine presence in Egypt, however, they started becoming a distinctive minority in Egypt around the early 18th century. The majority of Syro-Lebanese migrants who arrived in Egypt during this time were [[Francophone|French-speaking]] and highly influenced by the [[European Culture]]. By the dawn of the 20th century, the Syro-Lebanese of Egypt were considered a powerful and cosmopolitan community that played an important role in both Egypt's economy and culture. \n\nDue to the rise in nationalism along with the loss of economic freedoms during the 1950s, a part of Egypt's Syro-Lebanese community left the country immigrating to the [[Americas]], [[Europe]], and [[Australia]], as well as many returning to their native Lebanon (especially [[Beirut]]) and Syria. Notable descendants of Egypt's Syro-Lebanese community include the world-renowned Egyptian actor [[Omar Sharif]] (born Michel Chalhoub) and Egyptian film director [[Youssef Chahine]].\n\n==History==\nThe relations between Egypt and the [[Levant]] go back to ancient times. However, the earliest instance of modern Levantine migration to Egypt happened after 1724, when a schism in the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch]] resulted in a separate branch of Levantine Christians attached to Rome known as the [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Melkite Greek Catholics]]. Once the Syrian and Lebanese Greek Orthodox community was split, a migratory flow resulted in which Melkite Greek Catholics began leaving cities such as [[Damascus]], [[Aleppo]], [[Zahle]], and [[Sidon]] to move to Egypt. Regarding an early [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite]] presence in Egypt dating from the 18th century, it is said that the [[Holy See|Holy see of Rome]] appointed two Maronite priests to serve as advisers to the [[Franciscans]] who came from the Custody of the Holy Land to [[Evangelism|evangelize]] Egypt because \"no one knows the land and mentality of the Coptic Christians like the Maronites\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Catholics In Egypt Reflect Church's Rich And Varied Traditions |newspaper=L'Osservatore Romano|date=1 March 2000|volume=Weekly Edition in English|pages=6, 7|url=http://www.ewtn.com/library/CHISTORY/EGPTCATH.HTM}}</ref>[[File:Ikonenwand der Kirche des St. Saba(s), Alexandria, \u00c4gypten.jpg|thumb|Iconostasis of the Greek Orthodox Church of St. Sabbas, Alexandria, Egypt|235x235px]]Later during the mid-1800s, due to the [[1860 Lebanon conflict|political conflict]] that existed in Lebanon and Syria between the [[Christians|Christian]] and [[Druze]] religious sects, many [[Syrian people|Syrian]] and [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] Christians, as well as [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] and [[Jordanian people|Jordanian]] Christians to some extent, migrated to Egypt under the rule of [[Muhammad Ali Pasha]]. These Syro-Lebanese or [[Levant]]ine Christians, known in Egyptian Arabic as the \"Shawam\", were either of Greek Orthodox or Catholic (Melkite or Maronite) extraction. The reason immigrants from Lebanon and Syria were considered one ethnic group was because during the mid-1800s, Lebanon was not yet an independent state and was still part of [[Ottoman Syria]], or \"Bilad al-Sham\" in Arabic, hence their label as \"Shawam\" or \"Shami\".  Muhammad Ali Pasha endorsed various ethnic and religious groups, including Syro-Lebanese, [[Greeks in Egypt|Greeks]], [[Armenians in Egypt|Armenians]], [[Jews in Egypt|Jews]], [[Italians in Egypt|Italians]], and [[Maltese in Egypt|Maltese]] to settle in Egypt.<ref>{{cite book|last=Sol\u00e9|first=Robert|title=Birds of Passage|year=2000|publisher=Harvill Press|location=London, England|isbn=1860466974|url=https://archive.org/details/birdsofpassage00robe}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Sol\u00e9|first=Robert|title=Le Tarbouche|year=1992|publisher=Seuil|location=Paris|isbn=978-2020205108}}</ref>\nFrom the building of the Suez Canal to the creation of modern Downtown Cairo, Egypt\u2019s rulers went on a spending spree that attracted migrants from across the world. The Syro-Lebanese, who first migrated were [[French language|French-speaking]] and well-educated (largely due to [[Europe|European]] and [[American Home Missionary Society|American missionaries]]), had a mindset in the British-run economy of Egypt at the time. As a result, they were able to flourish as an energetic and cosmopolitan community until the [[Gamal Abdel Nasser|Nasser]] era of the mid-1950s, that adopted an Arabization mind set for the entire region.  Most of the Syro-Lebanese were self-employed businessmen or [[Artisan|craftsmen]] and had more of a \"[[Westernization|Westernized]]\" education than others. [[Robert Sol\u00e9]], a [[France|French]] author of Levantine-Egyptian descent, describes all of these aspects of the Syro-Lebanese community in Egypt in his book, \"Birds of Passage\", as well as in his other publications.<ref>{{cite book|last=Sol\u00e9|first=Robert|title=Birds of Passage|year=2000|publisher=Harvill Press|location=London, England|isbn=1860466974|url=https://archive.org/details/birdsofpassage00robe}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Sol\u00e9|first=Robert|title=Le Tarbouche|year=1992|publisher=Seuil|location=Paris|isbn=978-2020205108}}</ref>\n\nThe Syro-Lebanese established [[Greek Catholic Church|Melkite Greek-Catholic]] and Maronite Catholic churches throughout many areas of Egypt such as [[Cairo]], [[Alexandria]], [[Mansoura]], [[Suez]], [[Port Said]], and [[Tanta]]. The Greek Orthodox Syro-Lebanese experienced conflict trying to establish their own churches under their native [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch|Antiochian]] denomination, and became under the jurisdiction of the [[Greek Orthodox Church of Alexandria]], which was mainly run by an ethnic Greek clergy. \nIn Egypt, many families of Syro-Lebanese origin became successful in Egypt's business sector along with the established Armenian and Greek communities. Many were involved in Egypt's booming cotton industry. The famous Egyptian newspaper, \"[[Al-Ahram]]\", was created by the Syro-Lebanese Takla family in Egypt.<ref>{{cite book|last=Khoury|first=G\u00e9rard D.|title=S\u00e9lim Takla 1895-1945: Une Contribution \u00e0 L'ind\u00e9pendance Du Liban|year=2004|publisher=Karthala Editions|isbn=284586549X|pages=556|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iluH1VqaI5UC&pg=RA2-PA21-IA4&lpg=RA2-PA21-IA4&dq=takla+al-ahram&source=bl&ots=0Ndyxbiba-&sig=HvZt7lNGQuqPDa_VChc7ZGpB8bM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6zHRULeAF-XL0AGH4oDAAw&ved=0CEgQ6AEwAw}}</ref>\nSyro-Lebanese families dominated the publishing industry, owning major printing houses like Dar al-Hilal (est. 1892), which gave them enormous influence on the country\u2019s cultural life. Even Rose al-Youssef, the quintessential Egyptian cultural figure from the first half of the twentieth century, was originally Levantine of Turkish descent. The (then) irreverent political and literary magazine she founded and named after herself continues to this day, albeit in state hands like Al-Ahram. Even the material culture of Cairo has been suffused by Syro-Lebanese influence. The most prolific architect in Central Cairo between the 1930s and 1960s was Antoine Selim Nahhas, who is seen as the one of the modernist architects in Egypt. Nahhas, who built among other important buildings the Beirut National Museum, established a wildly successful practice in Cairo, where he designed buildings for the rich and famous, often Levantine-Egyptians like himself, such as the actor Farid al-Atrash. [[File:Syro-Lebanese Christian women.jpg|thumb|235x235px|Christian Syro-Lebanese women in Cairo, Egypt 1950's|alt=]]Even though the number of Levantine-Egyptians still in Egypt is drastically low today, the Syro-Lebanese community retains its strength in some aspects of the cultural and entertainment industries. Cairo\u2019s most famous restaurant entrepreneur, Nisha Sursock, comes from a prominent Beirut Greek Orthodox family.<ref>{{cite news|last=El Amrani|first=Issandr|title=Lebanese Played a Crucial Role in Shaping Modern Egyptian Culture|newspaper=The Daily Star|date=2004-02-27}}</ref>\n\nThe Levantine community in Egypt counted more than 100,000 members at the turn of the 20th century: civil servants, hairdressers, cobblers, drivers, engineers, dentists, doctors, shopkeepers, painters. Their aggregate wealth was reckoned at one and a half billion francs, that is 10% of the Egyptian GDP. Those who had capital invested it in small businesses (oil, soaps, tobacco, patisserie). Others created more important companies trading or producing salt, sodium, textiles, perfume, wood, silk. This economic success led to the foundation of schools, clubs, and charities, generally linked to a place of worship which was most of the time a church. A minority returned to their home village but the majority remained \u201csemi-detached\u201d, settling for several generations in Egypt without for all that involving themselves fully in the host society.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fadel|first=Marwan Abi|title=Syro-Lebanese Migration Towards Egypt|url=http://hemed.univ-lemans.fr/cours2010/en/co/module_5.html}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Mansoura]], a city that used to be under huge [[France|French]] and [[Europe|European]] influence. The Levantines excelled equally as lawyers, cotton trade entrepreneurs, large real-estate owners, medical doctors and pharmacists, department store and restaurant and hotel owners, bankers, and financial agents. They were also renowned for their large estates, like the heirs of Comte Khalil de Saab and the Sussah family, Naguib Bek Sursuq, and the 'izba of George Daoud. They owned several international hotels. For instance, Khalil Bahari owned the Semiramis Hotel, which included the best restaurant in Mansoura. Dhaher al-Rayyes was the owner of the largest hotel in Mansoura, the [[Paris]] Hotel, while his brother, Bichara, owned the Claridge Hotel, and a third brother owned the Imperial Hotel. The Shawam of Mansoura occupied key positions as medical doctors, showing why nearly half of the doctors in Mansoura used to be foreigners at that time, mainly Europeans. Levantines also notably became bank managers. Some Shawam earned the titles of Count, like Count Saab and Count Chedid. Others earned the titles of Pasha and Bek, while a few even earned the title of Emir (Prince), like the Lutfallah, and subsequently the [[Sursock family|Sursock]], family.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Abaza|first1=Mona|title=The Cotton Plantation Remembered: An Egyptian Family Story|date=15 November 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press}}</ref>\n\n==Identity==\n\nThe term \"Syro-Lebanese\" or \"Syrian-Lebanese\" is an [[umbrella term]] to identify the people of the Levant, especially the generations who lived when most of the region was known as [[Bilad al-Sham]], or [[Greater Syria]]. Between the late 18th century and early 20th century, thousands of Levantines left their homeland, mainly due to warfare, and Egypt became the first stop for many who aimed to reach the Western world. In Egypt, as well as other nations with Syrian and Lebanese diaspora communities, the Levantines mainly identified by religion and city of origin, rather than by ethnicity. For example, one could identify as a \"[[Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholic]] from [[Zahle]]\", while another could identify as \"[[Greek Orthodox Church|Greek Orthodox]] from [[Aleppo]]\". For the most part, religious denomination and city of origin were more important to the Levantines than an actual \"Levantine\" or \"Syro-Lebanese\" identity. This may explain why it was generally easy for the Syro-Lebanese to assimilate into their newly found homelands and mix with other Christian populations, especially in Egypt. However, the Egyptians, and especially the Coptic [[Coptic Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christians]], could easily point out a Levantine's non-native background due to their foreign Christian background, if not by their overall lighter skin tone. After generations of living in Egypt, most of this community's descendants, now with Egyptian nationality, tended to identify more as \"Egyptian\", rather than \"Levantine\", \"Syrian\", or \"Lebanese\", while still maintaining their original [[christian Denomination|Christian sect]] of identity. However, intermarriage for the Levantines in Egypt eventually became more common after generations, either with native Coptic Christians whom are in millions or with other foreign minority Christians such as [[Greek people|Greeks]], [[Armenian people|Armenians]], and [[Maltese people|Maltese]]. There was much less intermarriage between Levantine Christians and native Muslims, as marriage between Christians and Muslims is still considered taboo in Egypt.\n\n==Churches==\n\n[[Christianity]] is the dominant religion among Egyptians of Syro-Lebanese descent. The majority follow Greek Orthodox (originally [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch|Greek Orthodox Antiochian]], but then falling under [[Greek Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Greek Orthodox Alexandrian]] jurisdiction in Egypt), a founder sect of Christianity since the [[Greco-Roman world|Greco-Roman Egypt]], [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church]] and the [[Maronite Church]]. With [[Catholic school|Catholic education]] being popular among [[Christianity|Christian]] families in Egypt, many Levantines also naturally attended [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic churches]].\n\n\u2022 Greek Orthodox Churches ([[Greece|Greek]] [[Christian denomination|Church]]es):\n\n* [[Cairo]] - Greek Orthodox Church of St. George, Greek Catholic Cathedral of the Resurrection, Greek Catholic Annunciation Church, Greek Catholic Immaculate Conception Church, Greek Catholic St. George Church, Greek Catholic St. Mary of Peace Church, Greek Catholic St. Joseph Church, Greek Catholic St. Cyril Church\n* [[Alexandria, Egypt|Alexandria]] - Greek Catholic Dormition Cathedral, Saint Sabbas Greek Orthodox Church, Greek Catholic Immaculate Conception, Greek Catholic St. Joseph, \n* [[Damanhur]] - Saints Constantine and Helena Greek Orthodox Church\n* [[Damietta]] - Saint Nicholas Greek Orthodox Church, and an old Greek Catholic Church that was converted to a Coptic Orthodox Church.\n* [[El-Mahalla El-Kubra]] - Saint George Greek Orthodox Church, Saint Augustine Catholic Church\n* [[Mansoura]] - Saint Nicholas Greek Orthodox Church, Saints Athanasius and Cyril Greek Orthodox Church, Dormition Greek Catholic Church\n* [[Port Said]] - Saint Elias Greek Catholic Church\n* [[Shibin Al Kawm, Al Minufiyah|Shibin Al Kawm]] - Saint Spyridon Greek Orthodox Church\n* [[Tanta]] - Saint George Greek Orthodox Church, Dormition of the Holy Virgin Greek Orthodox Church, Presentation of the Lord Greek Orthodox Church, Saint Anne Greek Catholic Church\n* [[Zagazig]] - Three Hierarchs Greek Orthodox Church, Dormition of the Holy Virgin Greek Orthodox Church, Saint Joseph Catholic Church\n\n==Diaspora==\nThe number of Syro-Lebanese in Egypt has decreased due to the nationalization policies of the [[Gamal Abdel Nasser|Nasser]] government after the [[1952 Revolution|1952 revolution]].{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} As a result, there has been extensive migrations to other countries such as [[Canada]], the [[United States]], [[France]], [[Australia]], [[Switzerland]], and [[Belgium]]. The remaining Syro-Lebanese in Egypt began integrating into the rest of Egyptian society, including extensive intermarriage with [[Coptic Orthodox Church|Coptic Christians]] and Muslims. Today, most Egyptians of Levantine roots tend to identify more as Egyptian rather than Syrian or Lebanese, even though some traditionally belong to [[List of Christian denominations|Christian denominations]] like [[Greek Orthodox Church|Greek Orthodox]] other than Egypt's native [[Coptic Orthodox]], [[Coptic Catholic]], or native Protestant churches.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tewfik|first1=Paul Shoukri|title=The Syro-Lebanese of Egypt|date=17 December 2012}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nA large number of Syro-Lebanese families from Egypt now reside in [[Montreal]]; The communities of [[St. George Antiochian Orthodox Church (Montreal)|St. George Antiochian Orthodox Church]], Saint-Sauveur Melkite Greek-Catholic Cathedral, and St. Maron Church (Maronite Catholic), have many parishioners who are from Egypt or are descendants of Egyptian immigrants. Records from 1987 show that up to 250 families out of the total 1,300 registered families of [[St. George Antiochian Orthodox Church (Montreal)|St. George's Antiochian Orthodox Church of Montreal]] were originally from Egypt. In that same year, the Melkite [[Saint Sauveur Cathedral]] of Montreal reported to have approximately two-thirds of its 3,000 registered families originating from Egypt. Records from the St. Maron Church in Montreal show that out of its total 1,284 registered families in 1987, 600 of them were [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronites]] from Egypt.<ref>{{cite book |last=Magocsi |first=Paul Robert |year=1999 |title=Encyclopedia of Canada's Peoples |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dbUuX0mnvQMC&pg=PA460 |publisher=University of Toronto Press |page=460 |isbn=978-0-8020-2938-6}}</ref>\n\nExample of those [[Greek Catholic]] melkite [[Christianity|Christians]] who faced oppression from Nasser regime and was forced to get out residing in [[Europe]], [[Americas]] and [[Australia]] are; Absi, Ackaoui, Allouche, Anhoury, Arcache, Assouad, Ayrout, Ayoub, Azzam, Barakat, Behna, Bichara, Bittar, Boulad, Bahri, Cassis, Chahine, Chalhoub, Dabbour, Debban\u00e9, Doummar, Dahan, Eid, Fakhoury, Gargoura, Gorra, Haddad, Hawawini, Hobeika, Jaouich, Kassab, Kahil, Kahla, Kheir, Kfouri, Klat, Karam, Lahham, M\u00e9dawar, Michaka, Mirza, Mitri, Naoum, Nahas, Nimr, Rabbath, Rathie, Sarkis, Sednaoui, Sabet, Sabbagh, Samman, Sayeh, Sakakini, Sabounghi, Sol\u00e9, Toutounji,Talka, Tawil, Tagher, Tawa, Yansouni, Zalka, Zayat, Zananiri, Zogheb. <ref>{{cite web|last=Manzoni|first=Sandro|title=Alexandrie Info|url=http://www.aaha.ch/bulletins/pdf/Bull-26.pdf|accessdate=26 March 2020|quote=La plus grande partie de cette communaut\u00e9 a quite l'Egypte apres lets \u00e9v\u00e9nements de 1956 et les vagues de nationalisations nass\u00e9riennes. Beaucoup se sont install\u00e9s au Liban, en Europe (France et Suisse) et Am\u00e9rique (surtout Canada). }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Naaman|first=Abdallah|title=Histoire des Orientaux de France du Ier au XXe si\u00e8cle|year=2004|publisher=Ellipses|location=Paris|isbn=978-2729814052}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Habib Tawa]], French historian, specialist of this issue\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Demographics of Egypt}}\n{{Lebanese diaspora}}\n{{Syrian diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Asian diaspora in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Eastern Catholicism in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodoxy in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Egyptian people of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:Egyptian people of Palestinian descent]]\n[[Category:Egyptian people of Syrian descent]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Greek Orthodoxy in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Egypt]] \n[[Category:Jordanian diaspora]]\n[[Category:Lebanese diaspora by country|Egypt]]\n[[Category:Lebanese diaspora in Africa]]\n[[Category:Maronites by country]]\n[[Category:Melkite Greek Catholic Church in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Palestinian diaspora in the Arab world]]\n[[Category:Syrian diaspora in the Arab world]]\n[[Category:Syrian diaspora in Africa]]\n", "name_user": "JJNito197", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syro-Lebanese_in_Egypt"}
{"title_page": "Don Norman", "text_new": "{{for|the ice hockey coach|Don Norman (ice hockey)}}\n{{multiple issues|{{BLP primary sources|date=June 2011}}\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2011}}}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Don Norman\n| image = Donald Norman at AWF05.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Norman in 2005\n| birth_name = Donald Arthur Norman\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1935|12|25}}\n| birth_place = \n| residence = [[United States]]\n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| field = [[Cognitive science]]<br />[[Usability engineering]]\n| work_institutions = [[Northwestern University]]<br />[[University of California, San Diego]]<br />[[Nielsen Norman Group]]<br />[[KAIST|Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology]]\n| alma_mater = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]]<br />[[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| known_for = ''[[The Design of Everyday Things]]''<br />[[Cognitive ergonomics]]<br />[[User-centered design]]\n| thesis_title = Sensory Thresholds And Response Biases In Detection Experiments, A Theoretical And Experimental Analysis\n| thesis_year = 1962\n| doctoral_advisor = [[R. Duncan Luce]]\n| doctoral_students = {{plainlist|1=\n*[[Michael I. Jordan]]<br>[[Naomi Miyake]]<br>[[Abigail Sellen]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|jnd.org}}<ref name=\"jnd\" />\n}}\n\n'''Donald Arthur Norman''' (born December 25, 1935)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@uxpodcast/design-doing-with-don-norman-6434b022831b|title=Design Doing with Don Norman|last=Royal-Lawson|first=James|last2=Axbom|first2=Per|date=2016-08-24|website=Medium|publisher=UX Podcast|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-14|quote=Per: Born in 1935. James: Yeah, he actually turned 80 around about the same time as we had a Twitter conversation about this interview. Per: Exactly. It was December 25.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isni.org/isni/0000000122839155|title=ISNI 0000000122839155 - Donald A. Norman ( 1935- )|last=|first=|date=|website=International Standard Name Identifier (ISNI)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> is an American researcher, professor, and author. Norman is the director of The Design Lab at [[University of California, San Diego]].<ref name=\"Robbins, Gary\" /> He is best known for his books on design, especially ''[[The Design of Everyday Things]]''. He is widely regarded for his expertise in the fields of [[design]], [[usability engineering]], and [[cognitive science]].<ref name=\"Robbins, Gary\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/science/sdut-don-norman-homecoming-2014oct23-story.html|title=Don Norman has designs on your life|last=Robbins|first=Gary|date=2014|website=San Diego Union Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> He is a co-founder and consultant with the [[Nielsen Norman Group]]. He is also an [[IDEO]] fellow and a member of the Board of Trustees of [[IIT Institute of Design]] in Chicago. He also holds the title of [[Professor Emeritus]] of Cognitive Science at the [[University of California, San Diego]]. Norman is an active [[Distinguished Visiting Professor]] at the [[Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology]] (KAIST), where he spends two months a year teaching.{{When|date=February 2019}}\n\nMuch of Norman's work involves the advocacy of [[user-centered design]].<ref name=\"Zachry\">{{cite journal | last = Zachry | first = Mark | title = An Interview with Donald Norman | journal = Technical Communication Quarterly | volume = 14 | issue = 4 | date = October 2005 | page = 469 | doi = 10.1207/s15427625tcq1404_5}}</ref> His books all have the underlying purpose of furthering the field of design, from doors to computers. Norman has taken a controversial stance in saying that the [[design research]] community has had little impact in the innovation of products, and that while academics can help in refining existing products, it is technologists that accomplish the breakthroughs.<ref>{{ cite web | last = Norman | first = Donald | title = Technology First, Needs Last | url = http://jnd.org/dn.mss/technology_first_needs_last.html | accessdate = January 26, 2010 }}</ref> To this end, Norman named his website with the initialism ''[[Just-noticeable difference|JND]]'' (just-noticeable difference) to signify his endeavors to make a difference.<ref name=\"jnd\">{{cite web |url= http://www.jnd.org/about.html#jnd |title= What does ''jnd.org'' mean? |website= Just-Noticeable Difference |access-date= April 20, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140616113957/http://www.jnd.org/about.html#jnd |archive-date= June 16, 2014 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n== Early academics ==\nIn 1957, Norman received a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] degree in [[Electrical engineering|Electrical Engineering]] from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT).<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fi.edu/laureates/donald-norman|title=Donald Norman|date=2014-01-15|website=The Franklin Institute|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> Norman received a [[Master of Science|M.S.]] degree in Electrical Engineering from the University of Pennsylvania.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://fabbs.org/our_scientists/donald-norman-phd/|title=In Honor Of\u2026 Donald Norman|last=|first=|date=|website=Federation of Associations in Behavioral & Brain Sciences (FABBS)|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> He received a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[Psychology]] from the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\":2\" /> He was one of the earliest graduates from the [[Mathematical psychology|Mathematical Psychology]] group at University of Pennsylvania and his advisor was [[R. Duncan Luce|Duncan Luce]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAfter graduating, Norman took up a postdoctoral fellowship at the Center for Cognitive Studies at [[Harvard University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uxmastery.com/transcript-chat-don-norman/|title=Transcript: A Chat with Don Norman|last=|first=|date=2017|website=UX Mastery|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3S1XAgAAQBAJ&dq|title=The Open Mind: Cold War Politics and the Sciences of Human Nature|last=Cohen-Cole|first=Jamie|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=2014|isbn=9780226092331|location=|pages=176, 183|via=Google Books}}</ref> and within a year became a lecturer.\n\nAfter four years with the Center, Norman took a position as an associate professor in the Psychology Department at [[University of California, San Diego]] (UCSD). Norman applied his training as an engineer and computer scientist, and as an experimental and mathematical psychologist, to the emerging discipline of [[cognitive science]]. Norman eventually became founding chair of the Department of Cognitive Science and chair of the Department of Psychology.\n\nAt UCSD, Norman was a founder of the Institute for Cognitive Science and one of the organizers of the [[Cognitive Science Society]] (along with [[Roger Schank]], [[Allan M. Collins|Allan Collins]], and others), which held its first meeting at the UCSD campus in 1979.<ref name=\"cv\">{{cite web|url=http://jnd.org/docs/Don_Norman_Academic_Vita.pdf|title=Donald Norman Curriculum Vitae|last=Norman|first=Donald|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100203032311/http://www.jnd.org/docs/Don_Norman_Academic_Vita.pdf|archive-date=February 3, 2010|accessdate=January 26, 2010}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2019}}\n\nTogether with psychologist [[Tim Shallice]], Norman proposed a framework of attentional control of executive functioning.{{When|date=November 2019}} One of the components of the Norman-Shallice model is the [[supervisory attentional system]].<ref name=\"1a\">{{cite book | last = Friedenberg | first = Jay | author2 = Gordon Silverman | title = Cognitive Science: An Introduction of the Study of Mind | year = 2010 | publisher = SAGE Publications | location = United St ates of America | isbn = 978-1-4129-7761-6 | pages = 180\u2013182}}</ref>\n\n== Cognitive engineering career ==\nNorman made the transition from cognitive science to [[cognitive engineering]] by entering the field as a consultant and writer. His article \"The truth about Unix: ''The user interface is horrid''\"<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Norman | first1 = Don | title = The truth about Unix: The user interface is horrid | volume = 27 | url = http://www.bradleymonk.com/File:The_truth_about_Unix_Don_Norman.pdf | work = Datamation | issue = 12 | date = 1981}}</ref> in ''[[Datamation]]'' (1981) catapulted him to a position of prominence in the computer world.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}} Soon after, his career took off outside of academia, although he still remained active at UCSD until 1993. Norman continued his work to further [[human-centered design]] by serving on numerous university and government advisory boards such as the [[Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency]] (DARPA). He currently serves on numerous committees and advisory boards like at Motorola, the [[Toyota National College of Technology]], [[TED Conference]], [[Panasonic]], ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]'', and many more.\n\nNorman was also part of a select team flown in to investigate the 1979, [[Three Mile Island accident|Three Mile Island nuclear accident]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mindflowdesign.com/insights/user-centric-design-the-lessons-of-3-mile-island/|title=User-Centric Design - The Lessons of 3 Mile Island|date=2014-08-06|work=Mindflow Design|access-date=2018-04-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Norman left UCSD to join [[Apple Computer]], initially as an Apple Fellow as a User Experience Architect (the first use of the phrase \"[[User Experience]]\" in a job title<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lialina|first1=Olia|title=Rich User Experience, UX and Desktopization of War|url=http://contemporary-home-computing.org/RUE/|website=contemporary-home-computing.org|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Merholz|first1=Peter|title=Peter in Conversation with Don Norman About UX & Innovation|url=http://adaptivepath.org/ideas/e000862/|website=Adaptative Path|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=January 2016}}), and then as the Vice President of the [[Apple Advanced Technology Group|Advanced Technology Group]]. He later worked for [[Hewlett-Packard]] before joining with [[Jakob Nielsen (usability consultant)|Jakob Nielsen]] to form the [[Nielsen Norman Group]] in 1998. He returned to academia as a professor of [[computer science]] at [[Northwestern University]], where he was co-director of the [[Segal Design Institute]] until 2010. In 2014, he returned to UCSD to become director of the newly established The Design Lab housed at the [[California Institute for Telecommunications and Information Technology]].\n\nIn 2014, Norman returned to the University of California, San Diego as newly appointed director of The Design Lab.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2014/oct/23/don-norman-homecoming/|title=Don Norman has designs on your life|website=The San Diego Union-Tribune|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nNorman has received many awards for his work. He received two [[honorary degree]]s, one \"S. V. della laurea ad honorem\" in Psychology from the [[University of Padua]] in 1995 and one doctorate in Industrial Design and Engineering from [[Delft University of Technology]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unipd.it/en/university/history/honorary-degrees|title=Honorary Degrees|last=|first=|date=|website=Universit\u00e0 di Padova|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-14|quote=01/03/1995 - Honorary degree to Donald A. Norman in \"Psychology\"}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> In 2001, he was inducted as a [[Fellow]] of the [[Association for Computing Machinery]] (ACM) and won the Rigo Award from [[SIGDOC]], the Association for Computing Machinery's Special Interest Group (SIG) on the Design of Communication (DOC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sigdoc.acm.org/awards/rigo-award/|title=Rigo Award|website=Special Interest Group on Design of Communication|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> In 2006, he received the [[The Franklin Institute Awards|Benjamin Franklin Medal]] in Computer and Cognitive Science.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2009, Norman was elected an Honorary Fellow of the [[Design Research Society]].\n\n== Nielsen Norman Group ==\n{{main|Nielsen Norman Group}}\nNorman, alongside colleague Jakob Nielsen, formed the Nielsen Norman Group (NN/g) in 1998.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://theblog.adobe.com/where-did-the-term-user-experience-come-from/|title=Where Did the Term \"User Experience\" Come From?|last=|first=|date=2017-08-28|website=Adobe Blog|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13|quote=In 1998, he formed the Nielsen Norman Group alongside Jakob Nielsen, another pioneer of usability methods that remain widely used today, including the 10 Usability Heuristics.}}</ref> The company's vision is to help designers and other companies move toward more human-centered products and internet interactions, and are pioneers in the field of [[usability]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Quotes ==\n{{Wikiquote-inline}}\n* \"Academics get paid for being clever, not for being right.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=FUkXAQAAMAAJ&q=%22academics+get+paid+for+being+clever%22&dq=%22academics+get+paid+for+being+clever%22|title=Annual conference|last=|first=|publisher=Bureau of Economic and Business Research, Graduate School of Business, University of Utah|year=1996|isbn=|location=|pages=|accessdate=2011-06-24|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* \"Good design is actually a lot harder to notice than poor design, in part because good designs fit our needs so well that the design is invisible.\"<ref name=\"Norman 2013 xi\">{{Cite book|title=The Design of Everyday Things: Revised and Expanded Edition|last=Norman|first=Donald|publisher=|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=xi}}</ref>\n* \u201cA brilliant solution to the wrong problem can be worse than no solution at all: solve the correct problem.\u201d <ref name=\"Norman 2013 xi\" />\n* \u201cFail often, fail fast,\u201d<ref name=\"Norman 2013 xi\" />\n\n== User-centered design ==\nIn his book ''[[The Design of Everyday Things]]'', Norman uses the term \"[[user-centered design]]\" to describe design based on the needs of the user, leaving aside what he deems secondary issues like aesthetics. User-centered design involves simplifying the structure of tasks, making things visible, getting the mapping right, exploiting the powers of constraint, designing for error, explaining [[affordance]]s and [[seven stages of action]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nIn his book ''The Things that Make Us Smart: Defending the Human Attribute in the Age of the Machine'',<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0201626950/donnormanA/104-2013751-2967137|title=Things That Make us Smart: Defending Human Attributes in the Age of the Machine|last1=Norman|first1=Don|date=1993|publisher=Pursues Book Group}}</ref>{{Better source|date=April 2019}} Norman uses the term \u201ccognitive artifacts\u201d to describe \u201cthose artificial devices that maintain, display, or operate upon information in order to serve a representational function and that affect human cognitive performance\u201d.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} Similar to his ''The Design of Everyday Things'' book, Norman argues for the development of machines that fit our minds, rather than have our minds be conformed to the machine.\n\nOn the Revised Edition of ''The Design of Everyday Things,'' Norman backtracks on his previous claims about aesthetics and removed the term User-Centered Design altogether. In the preface of the book, he says :<blockquote>The first edition of the book focused upon making products understandable and usable. The total experience of a product covers much more than its usability: aesthetics, pleasure, and fun play critically important roles. There was no discussion of pleasure, enjoyment and emotion, Emotion is so important that I wrote an entire book, [[Emotional Design]], about the role it plays in design.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The design of everyday things|last=Norman, Donald A.|isbn=9780465050659|edition= Revised and expanded |location=New York, New York|oclc=849801329|date = November 5, 2013}}</ref></blockquote>He instead currently uses the term human-centered design and defines it as: \"an approach that puts human needs, capabilities, and behavior first, then designs to accommodate those needs, capabilities, and ways of behaving.\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\nHe is on numerous educational, private, and public sector advisory boards, including the editorial board of ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''. Norman published several important books during his time at UCSD, one of which, ''User Centered System Design'', obliquely referred to the university in the initials of its title. This is a list of select publications.\n\n=== Psychology books ===\n*{{Cite book|title=Learning and Memory|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=W H Freeman & Co.|year=1983|isbn=0716713004|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/humaninformation0000lind|url-access=registration|title=Human information processing: an introduction to psychology|last=Lindsay|first=Peter H.|last2=Norman|first2=Donald A.|publisher=Academic Press|year=1972|isbn=|location=|pages=}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Oden|first1=Gregg C.|last2=Lopes|first2=Lola L.|year=1997|title=Human Information Processing: An Introduction to Psychology by Peter H. Lindsay, Donald A. Norman|url=|journal=The American Journal of Psychology|volume=110|issue=4|pages=635\u2013641|doi=10.2307/1423414|jstor=1423414}}</ref>\n*{{Cite book|title=Memory and Attention: An Introduction to Human Information Processing|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=John Wiley & Sons Inc|year=1976|isbn=0471651370|edition= 2|series=Series in Psychology|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Memory and Attention: An Introduction to Human Information Processing|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=John Wiley & Sons Inc|year=1969|isbn=0471651311|location=|pages=}}\n\n=== Usability books ===\n*{{Cite book|title=The Design of Everyday Things|last=Norman|first=Don|publisher=Basic Books|year=2013|isbn=9780465050659|series=Revised and expanded|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Living with Complexity|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=MIT Press|year=2010|isbn=978-0262014861|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=The Design of Future Things|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=Basic Books|year=2007|isbn=978-0465002276|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Emotional Design: Why We Love (or Hate) Everyday Things|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=Basic Books|year=2005|isbn=0465051367|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=The Invisible Computer: Why Good Products Can Fail, the Personal Computer Is So Complex, and Information Appliances Are the Solution|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=MIT Press|year=1998|isbn=9780262140652|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Turn Signals Are The Facial Expressions Of Automobiles|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=Basic Books|year=1993|isbn=9780201622362|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Things That Make Us Smart: Defending Human Attributes In The Age Of The Machine|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=Basic Books|year=1993|isbn=0201626950|series=William Patrick Book|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=The Psychology of Everyday Things|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=Basic Books|year=1988|isbn=0465067093|edition= 1|series=|location=|pages=}}\n\n=== Other publications ===\n*''Direct manipulation interfaces'' (1985) about [[direct manipulation interface]]s in collaboration with E. L. Hutchins (first author) and J.D. Hollan\n*''User Centered System Design: New Perspectives on Human-Computer Interaction'' (1986) (editor in collaboration with Stephen Draper)\n*{{Cite AV media|url=|title=Defending Human Attributes in the Age of the Machine|date=1994|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|type=[[CD-ROM]] for Mac|language=English|publisher=[[Voyager Company]]|format=|asin=B000CIQ42I}} Combining his books, ''Design of Everyday Things'', ''Turn Signals Are the Facial Expressions of Automobiles'', ''Things That Make Us Smart'', with various technical reports.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cognitive engineering]]\n* [[Executive system]]\n* [[Human action cycle]]\n* [[Human-computer interaction]]\n* [[Human-centered design]]\n* [[User-centered design]]\n* [[Interaction design]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Donald Norman}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{official website|http://jnd.org/}}\n*{{TED speaker}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050418233410/http://www.interaction-design.org/references/authors/donald_a_norman.html Publications by Donald Norman] from Interaction-Design.org\n* [http://www.usabilityviews.com/userati_don_norman.html Donald Norman at Userati]\n* Video: [https://www.fi.edu/laureates/donald-norman Franklin Institute Award on Donald Norman] from April 2006 by the [[Franklin Institute]]\n*Video: {{YouTube|wQmwEjL6K1U|Lecture by Donald Norman on \"The Design of Future Things\" (at Stanford University, February 2007)}}\n*Video: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=flRuSn0df8Q Living With Complexity], April 2011 talk at Stanford University\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140222013504/http://vorkspace.com/blog/index.php/eternal-record-evening-don-norman/ An evening of UX Hacking with Don Norman at Stanford\" (Stanford University, December 17, 2013)]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach|aw}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[Barbara Mirel]]\n| title = [[Association for Computing Machinery|ACM]] [[SIGDOC]] Rigo Award\n| after = [[Stephen Doheny-Farina]]\n| years = 2001\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[Aravind Joshi]]\n| title = Benjamin Franklin Medal in Computer and Cognitive Science\n| after = [[Stuart Card]]\n| years = 2006\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Donald Norman}}\n{{Ambient intelligence}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norman, Donald}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. employees]]\n[[Category:Cognitive scientists]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania School of Engineering and Applied Science alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of California, San Diego faculty]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University faculty]]\n[[Category:American computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Association for Computing Machinery]]\n[[Category:Human\u2013computer interaction researchers]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Engineering]]\n[[Category:Design researchers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Cognitive Science Society]]\n[[Category:Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences fellows]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the ice hockey coach|Don Norman (ice hockey)}}\n{{multiple issues|{{BLP primary sources|date=June 2011}}\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2011}}}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Don Norman\n| image = Donald Norman at AWF05.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Norman in 2005\n| birth_name = Donald Arthur Norman\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1935|12|25}}\n| birth_place = \n| residence = [[United States]]\n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| field = [[Cognitive science]]<br />[[Usability engineering]]\n| work_institutions = [[Northwestern University]]<br />[[University of California, San Diego]]<br />[[Nielsen Norman Group]]<br />[[KAIST|Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology]]\n| alma_mater = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]]<br />[[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| known_for = ''[[The Design of Everyday Things]]''<br />[[Cognitive ergonomics]]<br />[[User-centered design]]\n| thesis_title = Sensory Thresholds And Response Biases In Detection Experiments, A Theoretical And Experimental Analysis\n| thesis_year = 1962\n| doctoral_advisor = [[R. Duncan Luce]]\n| doctoral_students = {{plainlist|1=\n*[[Michael I. Jordan]]<br>[[Naomi Miyake]]<br>[[Abigail Sellen]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|jnd.org}}<ref name=\"jnd\" />\n}}\n\n'''Donald Arthur Norman''' (born December 25, 1935)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@uxpodcast/design-doing-with-don-norman-6434b022831b|title=Design Doing with Don Norman|last=Royal-Lawson|first=James|last2=Axbom|first2=Per|date=2016-08-24|website=Medium|publisher=UX Podcast|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-14|quote=Per: Born in 1935. James: Yeah, he actually turned 80 around about the same time as we had a Twitter conversation about this interview. Per: Exactly. It was December 25.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isni.org/isni/0000000122839155|title=ISNI 0000000122839155 - Donald A. Norman ( 1935- )|last=|first=|date=|website=International Standard Name Identifier (ISNI)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> is an American researcher, professor, and author. Norman is the director of The Design Lab at [[University of California, San Diego]].<ref name=\"Robbins, Gary\" /> He is best known for his books on design, especially ''[[The Design of Everyday Things]]''. He is widely regarded for his expertise in the fields of [[design]], [[usability engineering]], and [[cognitive science]].<ref name=\"Robbins, Gary\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/science/sdut-don-norman-homecoming-2014oct23-story.html|title=Don Norman has designs on your life|last=Robbins|first=Gary|date=2014|website=San Diego Union Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> He is a co-founder and consultant with the [[Nielsen Norman Group]]. He is also an [[IDEO]] fellow and a member of the Board of Trustees of [[IIT Institute of Design]] in Chicago. He also holds the title of [[Professor Emeritus]] of Cognitive Science at the [[University of California, San Diego]]. Norman is an active [[Distinguished Visiting Professor]] at the [[Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology]] (KAIST), where he spends two months a year teaching.{{When|date=February 2019}}\n\nMuch of Norman's work involves the advocacy of [[user-centered design]].<ref name=\"Zachry\">{{cite journal | last = Zachry | first = Mark | title = An Interview with Donald Norman | journal = Technical Communication Quarterly | volume = 14 | issue = 4 | date = October 2005 | page = 469 | doi = 10.1207/s15427625tcq1404_5}}</ref> His books all have the underlying purpose of furthering the field of design, from doors to computers. Norman has taken a controversial stance in saying that the [[design research]] community has had little impact in the innovation of products, and that while academics can help in refining existing products, it is technologists that accomplish the breakthroughs.<ref>{{ cite web | last = Norman | first = Donald | title = Technology First, Needs Last | url = http://jnd.org/dn.mss/technology_first_needs_last.html | accessdate = January 26, 2010 }}</ref> To this end, Norman named his website with the initialism ''[[Just-noticeable difference|JND]]'' (just-noticeable difference) to signify his endeavors to make a difference.<ref name=\"jnd\">{{cite web |url= http://www.jnd.org/about.html#jnd |title= What does ''jnd.org'' mean? |website= Just-Noticeable Difference |access-date= April 20, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140616113957/http://www.jnd.org/about.html#jnd |archive-date= June 16, 2014 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n== Early academics ==\n\nIn 1957, Norman received a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] degree in [[Electrical engineering|Electrical Engineering]] from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT).<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fi.edu/laureates/donald-norman|title=Donald Norman|date=2014-01-15|website=The Franklin Institute|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> Norman received a [[Master of Science|M.S.]] degree in Electrical Engineering from the University of Pennsylvania.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://fabbs.org/our_scientists/donald-norman-phd/|title=In Honor Of\u2026 Donald Norman|last=|first=|date=|website=Federation of Associations in Behavioral & Brain Sciences (FABBS)|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> He received a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[Psychology]] from the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\":2\" /> He was one of the earliest graduates from the [[Mathematical psychology|Mathematical Psychology]] group at University of Pennsylvania and his advisor was [[R. Duncan Luce|Duncan Luce]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAfter graduating, Norman took up a postdoctoral fellowship at the Center for Cognitive Studies at [[Harvard University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uxmastery.com/transcript-chat-don-norman/|title=Transcript: A Chat with Don Norman|last=|first=|date=2017|website=UX Mastery|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3S1XAgAAQBAJ&dq|title=The Open Mind: Cold War Politics and the Sciences of Human Nature|last=Cohen-Cole|first=Jamie|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=2014|isbn=9780226092331|location=|pages=176, 183|via=Google Books}}</ref> and within a year became a lecturer.\n\nAfter four years with the Center, Norman took a position as an associate professor in the Psychology Department at [[University of California, San Diego]] (UCSD). Norman applied his training as an engineer and computer scientist, and as an experimental and mathematical psychologist, to the emerging discipline of [[cognitive science]]. Norman eventually became founding chair of the Department of Cognitive Science and chair of the Department of Psychology.\n\nAt UCSD, Norman was a founder of the Institute for Cognitive Science and one of the organizers of the [[Cognitive Science Society]] (along with [[Roger Schank]], [[Allan M. Collins|Allan Collins]], and others), which held its first meeting at the UCSD campus in 1979.<ref name=\"cv\">{{cite web|url=http://jnd.org/docs/Don_Norman_Academic_Vita.pdf|title=Donald Norman Curriculum Vitae|last=Norman|first=Donald|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100203032311/http://www.jnd.org/docs/Don_Norman_Academic_Vita.pdf|archive-date=February 3, 2010|accessdate=January 26, 2010}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2019}}\n\nTogether with psychologist [[Tim Shallice]], Norman proposed a framework of attentional control of executive functioning.{{When|date=November 2019}} One of the components of the Norman-Shallice model is the [[supervisory attentional system]].<ref name=\"1a\">{{cite book | last = Friedenberg | first = Jay | author2 = Gordon Silverman | title = Cognitive Science: An Introduction of the Study of Mind | year = 2010 | publisher = SAGE Publications | location = United St ates of America | isbn = 978-1-4129-7761-6 | pages = 180\u2013182}}</ref>\n\n== Cognitive engineering career ==\n\nNorman made the transition from cognitive science to [[cognitive engineering]] by entering the field as a consultant and writer. His article \"The truth about Unix: ''The user interface is horrid''\"<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Norman | first1 = Don | title = The truth about Unix: The user interface is horrid | volume = 27 | url = http://www.bradleymonk.com/File:The_truth_about_Unix_Don_Norman.pdf | work = Datamation | issue = 12 | date = 1981}}</ref> in ''[[Datamation]]'' (1981) catapulted him to a position of prominence in the computer world.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}} Soon after, his career took off outside of academia, although he still remained active at UCSD until 1993. Norman continued his work to further [[human-centered design]] by serving on numerous university and government advisory boards such as the [[Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency]] (DARPA). He currently serves on numerous committees and advisory boards like at Motorola, the [[Toyota National College of Technology]], [[TED Conference]], [[Panasonic]], ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]'', and many more.\n\nNorman was also part of a select team flown in to investigate the 1979, [[Three Mile Island accident|Three Mile Island nuclear accident]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mindflowdesign.com/insights/user-centric-design-the-lessons-of-3-mile-island/|title=User-Centric Design - The Lessons of 3 Mile Island|date=2014-08-06|work=Mindflow Design|access-date=2018-04-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Norman left UCSD to join [[Apple Computer]], initially as an Apple Fellow as a User Experience Architect (the first use of the phrase \"[[User Experience]]\" in a job title<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lialina|first1=Olia|title=Rich User Experience, UX and Desktopization of War|url=http://contemporary-home-computing.org/RUE/|website=contemporary-home-computing.org|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Merholz|first1=Peter|title=Peter in Conversation with Don Norman About UX & Innovation|url=http://adaptivepath.org/ideas/e000862/|website=Adaptative Path|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=January 2016}}), and then as the Vice President of the [[Apple Advanced Technology Group|Advanced Technology Group]]. He later worked for [[Hewlett-Packard]] before joining with [[Jakob Nielsen (usability consultant)|Jakob Nielsen]] to form the [[Nielsen Norman Group]] in 1998. He returned to academia as a professor of [[computer science]] at [[Northwestern University]], where he was co-director of the [[Segal Design Institute]] until 2010. In 2014, he returned to UCSD to become director of the newly established The Design Lab housed at the [[California Institute for Telecommunications and Information Technology]].\n\nIn 2014, Norman returned to the University of California, San Diego as newly appointed director of The Design Lab.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2014/oct/23/don-norman-homecoming/|title=Don Norman has designs on your life|website=The San Diego Union-Tribune|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nNorman has received many awards for his work. He received two [[Honorary degree|honorary degrees]], one \"S. V. della laurea ad honorem\" in Psychology from the [[University of Padua]] in 1995 and one doctorate in Industrial Design and Engineering from [[Delft University of Technology]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unipd.it/en/university/history/honorary-degrees|title=Honorary Degrees|last=|first=|date=|website=Universit\u00e0 di Padova|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-14|quote=01/03/1995 - Honorary degree to Donald A. Norman in \"Psychology\"}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> In 2001, he was inducted as a [[Fellow]] of the [[Association for Computing Machinery]] (ACM) and won the Rigo Award from [[SIGDOC]], the Association for Computing Machinery's Special Interest Group (SIG) on the Design of Communication (DOC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sigdoc.acm.org/awards/rigo-award/|title=Rigo Award|website=Special Interest Group on Design of Communication|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> In 2006, he received the [[The Franklin Institute Awards|Benjamin Franklin Medal]] in Computer and Cognitive Science.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2009, Norman was elected an Honorary Fellow of the [[Design Research Society]].\n\n== Nielsen Norman Group ==\n{{main|Nielsen Norman Group}}\nNorman, alongside colleague Jakob Nielsen, formed the Nielsen Norman Group (NN/g) in 1998.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://theblog.adobe.com/where-did-the-term-user-experience-come-from/|title=Where Did the Term \"User Experience\" Come From?|last=|first=|date=2017-08-28|website=Adobe Blog|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13|quote=In 1998, he formed the Nielsen Norman Group alongside Jakob Nielsen, another pioneer of usability methods that remain widely used today, including the 10 Usability Heuristics.}}</ref> The company\u2019s vision is to help designers and other companies move toward more human-centered products and internet interactions, and are pioneers in the field of [[usability]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Quotes ==\n{{Wikiquote-inline}}\n\n* \"Academics get paid for being clever, not for being right.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=FUkXAQAAMAAJ&q=%22academics+get+paid+for+being+clever%22&dq=%22academics+get+paid+for+being+clever%22|title=Annual conference|last=|first=|publisher=Bureau of Economic and Business Research, Graduate School of Business, University of Utah|year=1996|isbn=|location=|pages=|accessdate=2011-06-24|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* \"Good design is actually a lot harder to notice than poor design, in part because good designs fit our needs so well that the design is invisible.\"<ref name=\"Norman 2013 xi\">{{Cite book|title=The Design of Everyday Things: Revised and Expanded Edition|last=Norman|first=Donald|publisher=|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=xi}}</ref>\n* \u201cA brilliant solution to the wrong problem can be worse than no solution at all: solve the correct problem.\u201d <ref name=\"Norman 2013 xi\" />\n* \u201cFail often, fail fast,\u201d<ref name=\"Norman 2013 xi\" />\n\n== User-centered design ==\n\nIn his book ''[[The Design of Everyday Things]]'', Norman uses the term \"[[user-centered design]]\" to describe design based on the needs of the user, leaving aside what he deems secondary issues like aesthetics. User-centered design involves simplifying the structure of tasks, making things visible, getting the mapping right, exploiting the powers of constraint, designing for error, explaining [[affordance]]s and [[seven stages of action]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nIn his book ''The Things that Make Us Smart: Defending the Human Attribute in the Age of the Machine'',<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0201626950/donnormanA/104-2013751-2967137|title=Things That Make us Smart: Defending Human Attributes in the Age of the Machine|last1=Norman|first1=Don|date=1993|publisher=Pursues Book Group}}</ref>{{Better source|date=April 2019}} Norman uses the term \u201ccognitive artifacts\u201d to describe \u201cthose artificial devices that maintain, display, or operate upon information in order to serve a representational function and that affect human cognitive performance\u201d.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} Similar to his ''The Design of Everyday Things'' book, Norman argues for the development of machines that fit our minds, rather than have our minds be conformed to the machine.\n\nOn the Revised Edition of ''The Design of Everyday Things,'' Norman backtracks on his previous claims about aesthetics and removed the term User-Centered Design altogether. In the preface of the book, he says :<blockquote>The first edition of the book focused upon making products understandable and usable. The total experience of a product covers much more than its usability: aesthetics, pleasure, and fun play critically important roles. There was no discussion of pleasure, enjoyment and emotion, Emotion is so important that I wrote an entire book, [[Emotional Design]], about the role it plays in design.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The design of everyday things|last=Norman, Donald A.|isbn=9780465050659|edition= Revised and expanded |location=New York, New York|oclc=849801329|date = November 5, 2013}}</ref></blockquote>He instead currently uses the term human-centered design and defines it as: \"an approach that puts human needs, capabilities, and behavior first, then designs to accommodate those needs, capabilities, and ways of behaving.\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\nHe is on numerous educational, private, and public sector advisory boards, including the editorial board of ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''. Norman published several important books during his time at UCSD, one of which, ''User Centered System Design'', obliquely referred to the university in the initials of its title. This is a list of select publications.\n\n=== Psychology books ===\n\n*{{Cite book|title=Learning and Memory|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=W H Freeman & Co.|year=1983|isbn=0716713004|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/humaninformation0000lind|url-access=registration|title=Human information processing: an introduction to psychology|last=Lindsay|first=Peter H.|last2=Norman|first2=Donald A.|publisher=Academic Press|year=1972|isbn=|location=|pages=}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Oden|first1=Gregg C.|last2=Lopes|first2=Lola L.|year=1997|title=Human Information Processing: An Introduction to Psychology by Peter H. Lindsay, Donald A. Norman|url=|journal=The American Journal of Psychology|volume=110|issue=4|pages=635\u2013641|doi=10.2307/1423414|jstor=1423414}}</ref>\n*{{Cite book|title=Memory and Attention: An Introduction to Human Information Processing|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=John Wiley & Sons Inc|year=1976|isbn=0471651370|edition= 2|series=Series in Psychology|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Memory and Attention: An Introduction to Human Information Processing|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=John Wiley & Sons Inc|year=1969|isbn=0471651311|location=|pages=}}\n\n=== Usability books ===\n\n*{{Cite book|title=The Design of Everyday Things|last=Norman|first=Don|publisher=Basic Books|year=2013|isbn=9780465050659|series=Revised and expanded|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Living with Complexity|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=MIT Press|year=2010|isbn=978-0262014861|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=The Design of Future Things|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=Basic Books|year=2007|isbn=978-0465002276|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Emotional Design: Why We Love (or Hate) Everyday Things|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=Basic Books|year=2005|isbn=0465051367|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=The Invisible Computer: Why Good Products Can Fail, the Personal Computer Is So Complex, and Information Appliances Are the Solution|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=MIT Press|year=1998|isbn=9780262140652|location=Cambridge, Mass.|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Turn Signals Are The Facial Expressions Of Automobiles|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=Basic Books|year=1993|isbn=9780201622362|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Things That Make Us Smart: Defending Human Attributes In The Age Of The Machine|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=Basic Books|year=1993|isbn=0201626950|series=William Patrick Book|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=The Psychology of Everyday Things|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|publisher=Basic Books|year=1988|isbn=0465067093|edition= 1|series=|location=|pages=}}\n\n=== Other publications ===\n\n*''Direct manipulation interfaces'' (1985) about [[direct manipulation interface]]s in collaboration with E. L. Hutchins (first author) and J.D. Hollan\n*''User Centered System Design: New Perspectives on Human-Computer Interaction'' (1986) (editor in collaboration with Stephen Draper)\n*{{Cite AV media|url=|title=Defending Human Attributes in the Age of the Machine|date=1994|last=Norman|first=Donald A.|type=[[CD-ROM]] for Mac|language=English|publisher=[[Voyager Company]]|format=|asin=B000CIQ42I}} Combining his books, ''Design of Everyday Things'', ''Turn Signals Are the Facial Expressions of Automobiles'', ''Things That Make Us Smart'', with various technical reports.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cognitive engineering]]\n* [[Executive system]]\n* [[Human action cycle]]\n* [[Human-computer interaction]]\n* [[Human-centered design]]\n* [[User-centered design]]\n* [[Interaction design]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons cat|Donald Norman}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n*{{official website|http://jnd.org/}}\n*{{TED speaker}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050418233410/http://www.interaction-design.org/references/authors/donald_a_norman.html Publications by Donald Norman] from Interaction-Design.org\n* [http://www.usabilityviews.com/userati_don_norman.html Donald Norman at Userati]\n* Video: [https://www.fi.edu/laureates/donald-norman Franklin Institute Award on Donald Norman] from April 2006 by the [[Franklin Institute]]\n*Video: {{YouTube|wQmwEjL6K1U|Lecture by Donald Norman on \"The Design of Future Things\" (at Stanford University, February 2007)}}\n*Video: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=flRuSn0df8Q Living With Complexity], April 2011 talk at Stanford University\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140222013504/http://vorkspace.com/blog/index.php/eternal-record-evening-don-norman/ An evening of UX Hacking with Don Norman at Stanford\" (Stanford University, December 17, 2013)]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach|aw}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[Barbara Mirel]]\n| title = [[Association for Computing Machinery|ACM]] [[SIGDOC]] Rigo Award\n| after = [[Stephen Doheny-Farina]]\n| years = 2001\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[Aravind Joshi]]\n| title = Benjamin Franklin Medal in Computer and Cognitive Science\n| after = [[Stuart Card]]\n| years = 2006\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Donald Norman}}\n{{Ambient intelligence}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norman, Donald}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. employees]]\n[[Category:Cognitive scientists]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania School of Engineering and Applied Science alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of California, San Diego faculty]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University faculty]]\n[[Category:American computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Association for Computing Machinery]]\n[[Category:Human\u2013computer interaction researchers]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Engineering]]\n[[Category:Design researchers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Cognitive Science Society]]\n[[Category:Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences fellows]]\n", "name_user": "Jamesmcmahon0", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_Norman"}
{"title_page": "Genealogy book", "text_new": "A '''genealogy book''' or register is used in [[Asia]] and [[Europe]] to record the family history of ancestors. \n\n==Greater China==\n{{Main|Zupu}}\n{{Chinese\n|title=zupu\n|s=\u65cf\u8c31\n|t=\u65cf\u8b5c\n|p=z\u00fap\u01d4\n}}\nIt is the [[Chinese tradition]] to record family members in a book, including every male born in the family, who they are married to, etc. Traditionally, only males' names are recorded in the books. \n\nDuring the [[Cultural revolution]], many of the books were destroyed, because they were considered by the [[Chinese communist party]] as among the [[Four Olds]] to be eschewed. Therefore much valuable cultural history was destroyed forever. In [[Taiwan]], [[Hong Kong]], and areas untouched by the revolution, many Chinese people still kept their genealogy books, some of which are thousands of years old.\nAccording to Guinness World Record, the oldest genealogy book is that of the Confucius family.\n\n==India==\nIn India, the [[Hindu genealogy registers at Haridwar]] have been a subject of study for many years and have been microfilmed by [[Genealogical Society of Utah]] (GSU) USA.<ref>[http://www.gensocietyofutah.org/country.asp?countryid=408 India] ''[[Genealogical Society of Utah]]''.</ref>\nIn [[India]], [[Michael Lobo]] has been involved in documenting and compiling the history and genealogy of families belonging to the [[Mangalorean Catholic]] community since 1993, under a research project entitled \"A Genealogical Encyclopaedia of Mangalorean Catholic Families\".<ref name=\"lobo\"/> As of 2009, his work covers over a thousand families and is being continually updated with names and records of new families.<ref name=\"lobo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/chan/achievers_view.asp?a_id=10|title= Dr. Michael Lobo: Probing family roots and history|first=Richie|last=Lasrado|publisher=[[Daiji World|Daijiworld Media]]|accessdate=2008-10-20}}</ref> Lobo claims  that the Mangalorean Catholic community has the distinction of being the only community in the world to possess its own genealogical encyclopaedia.<ref name=\"lobo\"/>\n\n==Ireland==\nGenealogy has been a fundamental part of Irish culture since prehistory. Of the many surviving manuscripts, a large number are devoted to genealogy, either for a single family, or many. It was practised in both [[Gaels|Gaelic]] and [[Anglo-Normans|Anglo-Norman]] Ireland. A number of the more notable books include:\n\n* [[Leabhar na nGenealach]] (The Great Book of Irish Genealogies)\n*  The \u00d3 Cl\u00e9irigh Book of Genealogies\n* [[The Book of the Burkes]]\n* [[Leabhar Adhamh \u00d3 Cian\u00e1in]]\n* [[An Leabhar Muimhneach]]\n* [[Leabhar Donn]]\n\nFamilies who were professional historians included [[Clan \u00d3 Duibhgeann\u00e1in]], [[\u00d3 Cl\u00e9irigh]], [[Clan MacFhirbhisigh]], [[\u00d3 Maolconaire]].\n\n==Korea==\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|title=jokbo\n|hangul=\uc871\ubcf4\n|hanja=\u65cf\u8b5c\n|rr=jokbo\n|mr=chokpo\n}}\nIn Korea the genealogy book is called '''jokbo''' or '''chokbo'''.  Each family has a ''jokbo'' which is passed down through generations, and copies are often printed and distributed among family members as necessary.  The firstborn son of each family (in a form of [[primogeniture]]) inherits the original ''jokbo'' (as opposed to the copies) and continues the genealogy and family line.  It was often used in pre-modern (i.e., post-Joseon period) [[Korea]] as proof of being of the [[yangban]] class.\n\nWhile many clans still maintain a ''jokbo'', its function (which was very important, heavily relied upon, and legally binding before the modern era) is largely relegated to clan record-keeping and other minor (i.e., not legally binding) social roles.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Genealogy]]\n*[[Family tree]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Genealogy Book}}\n[[Category:Family registers]]\n", "text_old": "A '''genealogy book''' or register is used in [[Asia]] and [[Europe]] to record the family history of ancestors. \n\n==China==\n{{Main|Zupu}}\n{{Chinese\n|title=zupu\n|s=\u65cf\u8c31\n|t=\u65cf\u8b5c\n|p=z\u00fap\u01d4\n}}\nIt is the [[Chinese tradition]] to record family members in a book, including every male born in the family, who they are married to, etc. Traditionally, only males' names are recorded in the books. \n\nDuring the [[Cultural revolution]], many of the books were destroyed, because they were considered by the [[Chinese communist party]] as among the [[Four Olds]] to be eschewed. Therefore much valuable cultural history was destroyed forever. In [[Taiwan]], [[Hong Kong]], and areas untouched by the revolution, many Chinese people still kept their genealogy books, some of which are thousands of years old.\nAccording to Guinness World Record, the oldest genealogy book is that of the Confucius family.\n\n==India==\nIn India, the [[Hindu genealogy registers at Haridwar]] have been a subject of study for many years and have been microfilmed by [[Genealogical Society of Utah]] (GSU) USA.<ref>[http://www.gensocietyofutah.org/country.asp?countryid=408 India] ''[[Genealogical Society of Utah]]''.</ref>\nIn [[India]], [[Michael Lobo]] has been involved in documenting and compiling the history and genealogy of families belonging to the [[Mangalorean Catholic]] community since 1993, under a research project entitled \"A Genealogical Encyclopaedia of Mangalorean Catholic Families\".<ref name=\"lobo\"/> As of 2009, his work covers over a thousand families and is being continually updated with names and records of new families.<ref name=\"lobo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/chan/achievers_view.asp?a_id=10|title= Dr. Michael Lobo: Probing family roots and history|first=Richie|last=Lasrado|publisher=[[Daiji World|Daijiworld Media]]|accessdate=2008-10-20}}</ref> Lobo claims  that the Mangalorean Catholic community has the distinction of being the only community in the world to possess its own genealogical encyclopaedia.<ref name=\"lobo\"/>\n\n==Ireland==\nGenealogy has been a fundamental part of Irish culture since prehistory. Of the many surviving manuscripts, a large number are devoted to genealogy, either for a single family, or many. It was practised in both [[Gaels|Gaelic]] and [[Anglo-Normans|Anglo-Norman]] Ireland. A number of the more notable books include:\n\n* [[Leabhar na nGenealach]] (The Great Book of Irish Genealogies)\n*  The \u00d3 Cl\u00e9irigh Book of Genealogies\n* [[The Book of the Burkes]]\n* [[Leabhar Adhamh \u00d3 Cian\u00e1in]]\n* [[An Leabhar Muimhneach]]\n* [[Leabhar Donn]]\n\nFamilies who were professional historians included [[Clan \u00d3 Duibhgeann\u00e1in]], [[\u00d3 Cl\u00e9irigh]], [[Clan MacFhirbhisigh]], [[\u00d3 Maolconaire]].\n\n==Korea==\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|title=jokbo\n|hangul=\uc871\ubcf4\n|hanja=\u65cf\u8b5c\n|rr=jokbo\n|mr=chokpo\n}}\nIn Korea the genealogy book is called '''jokbo''' or '''chokbo'''.  Each family has a ''jokbo'' which is passed down through generations, and copies are often printed and distributed among family members as necessary.  The firstborn son of each family (in a form of [[primogeniture]]) inherits the original ''jokbo'' (as opposed to the copies) and continues the genealogy and family line.  It was often used in pre-modern (i.e., post-Joseon period) [[Korea]] as proof of being of the [[yangban]] class.\n\nWhile many clans still maintain a ''jokbo'', its function (which was very important, heavily relied upon, and legally binding before the modern era) is largely relegated to clan record-keeping and other minor (i.e., not legally binding) social roles.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Genealogy]]\n*[[Family tree]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Genealogy Book}}\n[[Category:Family registers]]\n", "name_user": "Braydench", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGreater China", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genealogy_book"}
